National Parks Biodiversity Analysis Portfolio Project

Executive Summary

This comprehensive data science project demonstrates advanced Python capabilities in data extraction, cleaning, visualization, and statistical analysis using real-world biodiversity data from U.S. National Parks. The analysis reveals critical insights into species distribution, conservation patterns, and park-specific biodiversity metrics.

Project Objectives

  • Data Engineering: Load, clean, and transform biodiversity datasets
  • Exploratory Data Analysis: Uncover patterns in species distribution and conservation status
  • Statistical Analysis: Perform hypothesis testing to validate findings
  • Data Visualization: Create compelling visualizations to communicate insights
  • Business Intelligence: Generate actionable recommendations for conservation efforts

Dataset Overview

  • observations.csv: Species observation counts across national parks
  • species_info.csv: Comprehensive species information including taxonomy and conservation status
  • Analysis Period: Multi-year biodiversity survey data
  • Scope: Four major U.S. National Parks

Key Technologies Demonstrated

  • Python Libraries: pandas, numpy, matplotlib, seaborn, scipy
  • Data Analysis: Statistical testing, hypothesis validation
  • Visualization: Professional-grade charts and insights
  • Documentation: Comprehensive reporting and analysis interpretation

2. Data Quality Assessment & Profiling

Conducting comprehensive data quality checks to identify potential issues, missing values, and data types. This step is crucial for ensuring reliable analysis results.

Data Quality Insights

Key Findings from Data Quality Assessment:

  1. Conservation Status Data Gap: The conservation_status field shows significant missing data (~92% null values), indicating that most species in the dataset do not have formal conservation status classifications. This is actually typical in biodiversity datasets, as many species are not formally assessed.

  2. Data Completeness: The observations dataset appears complete with no missing values, demonstrating high-quality data collection practices.

  3. Data Types: All columns have appropriate data types for analysis, with numeric values properly formatted for statistical operations.

Analytical Implications:

  • Conservation status analysis will focus on species WITH known status
  • Missing conservation data likely represents "Least Concern" or unstudied species
  • High data quality in observations enables robust statistical analysis

ax4.plot(sorted_obs, cumulative, linewidth=2, color='purple')
ax4.set_xlabel('Observation Count', fontsize=12)
ax4.set_ylabel('Cumulative Probability', fontsize=12)
ax4.set_title('Cumulative Distribution Function', fontsize=13, fontweight='bold')

fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(16, 6))

# Add value labels on bars
for i, (bar, value) in enumerate(zip(bars, category_counts.values)):
    ax1.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width()/2, bar.get_height() + 10, 
             f'{value:,}', ha='center', va='bottom', fontweight='bold', fontsize=9)

# Pie chart for proportional view
wedges, texts, autotexts = ax2.pie(category_counts.values, labels=category_counts.index,

ax2.set_title('Proportional Distribution of Species Categories', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')

# Detailed analysis
print("SPECIES COMPOSITION INSIGHTS:")
print("=" * 50)
total_species = len(species_info_df)

print(f"Number of Taxonomic Categories: {len(category_counts)}")

print(f"\nCategory Breakdown:")
for i, (category, count) in enumerate(category_counts.items(), 1):
    percentage = (count / total_species) * 100
    print(f"  {i}. {category}: {count:,} species ({percentage:.1f}%)")

# Statistical insights
dominant_category = category_counts.index[0]
dominant_percentage = (category_counts.iloc[0] / total_species) * 100
print(f"\nKey Findings:")
print(f"   Dominant Category: {dominant_category} ({dominant_percentage:.1f}% of all species)")
print(f"   Category Diversity: {len(category_counts)} different taxonomic groups represented")

# Calculate diversity metrics
from scipy.stats import entropy
category_proportions = category_counts / category_counts.sum()
shannon_diversity = entropy(category_proportions, base=2)
print(f"   Shannon Diversity Index: {shannon_diversity:.2f} (higher = more diverse)")

# Ecological implications
print(f"\nEcological Implications:")
if dominant_percentage > 50:
    print(f"   Dataset is dominated by {dominant_category}, indicating plant-heavy ecosystem focus")
else:
    print(f"   Relatively balanced taxonomic representation across categories")

animal_categories = [cat for cat in category_counts.index if 'Plant' not in cat]
animal_species = sum(category_counts[cat] for cat in animal_categories)
animal_percentage = (animal_species / total_species) * 100
print(f"   Animal species represent {animal_percentage:.1f}% of the dataset")
print(f"   Plant species represent {100 - animal_percentage:.1f}% of the dataset")

# Statistical significance testing
from scipy.stats import kruskal
parks_list = [group['observations'].values for name, group in observations_df.groupby('park_name')]
h_stat, p_value = kruskal(*parks_list)

print(f"\nSTATISTICAL SIGNIFICANCE TEST:")
print(f"Kruskal-Wallis H-test for differences between parks:")
print(f"   H-statistic: {h_stat:.3f}")
print(f"   p-value: {p_value:.6f}")
print(f"   Result: {'Significant differences between parks' if p_value < 0.05 else 'No significant differences'} ( = 0.05)")

# Ecological insights
print(f"\nECOLOGICAL INSIGHTS:")

Are the differences between species and their conservation status significant?

9. Statistical Hypothesis Testing

Research Question: Is there a statistically significant relationship between species category and conservation status?

Hypothesis Framework:

  • Null Hypothesis (H): Conservation status is independent of species category
  • Alternative Hypothesis (H): Conservation status is dependent on species category
  • Test: Chi-squared test of independence
  • Significance Level: = 0.05

Business Application: Statistical validation of observed patterns ensures our conservation recommendations are based on statistically sound evidence rather than apparent trends that could be due to chance.

In[23]:
import scipy.stats as stats

# Comprehensive statistical hypothesis testing
print("STATISTICAL HYPOTHESIS TESTING ANALYSIS")
print("=" * 55)

# Prepare data for chi-squared test (only include species with known conservation status)
analysis_df = species_info_df.dropna(subset=['conservation_status']).copy()

print(f"Statistical Test Setup:")
print(f"   Sample Size: {len(analysis_df):,} species with known conservation status")
print(f"   Categories: {analysis_df['category'].nunique()}")
print(f"   Conservation Statuses: {analysis_df['conservation_status'].nunique()}")

# Create contingency table
contingency = pd.crosstab(analysis_df['category'], analysis_df['conservation_status'])
print(f"\nContingency Table Dimensions: {contingency.shape[0]}  {contingency.shape[1]}")

# Display the contingency table
print(f"\nCONTINGENCY TABLE:")
print("=" * 30)
print(contingency)

# Perform Chi-squared test
chi2, pval, dof, expected = stats.chi2_contingency(contingency)

# Calculate effect size (Cramr's V)
n = contingency.sum().sum()
cramers_v = np.sqrt(chi2 / (n * (min(contingency.shape) - 1)))

# Create comprehensive visualization
fig, ((ax1, ax2), (ax3, ax4)) = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(16, 12))
fig.suptitle('Statistical Analysis: Species Category vs Conservation Status', fontsize=16, fontweight='bold', y=0.98)

# 1. Heatmap of observed frequencies
sns.heatmap(contingency, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', 
           cbar_kws={'label': 'Number of Species'}, linewidths=0.5, ax=ax1)
ax1.set_title('Observed Frequencies', fontsize=13, fontweight='bold')
ax1.set_xlabel('Conservation Status', fontsize=12)
ax1.set_ylabel('Species Category', fontsize=12)

# 2. Heatmap of expected frequencies
expected_df = pd.DataFrame(expected, index=contingency.index, columns=contingency.columns)
sns.heatmap(expected_df, annot=True, fmt='.1f', cmap='Oranges', 
           cbar_kws={'label': 'Expected Count'}, linewidths=0.5, ax=ax2)
ax2.set_title('Expected Frequencies (Under H)', fontsize=13, fontweight='bold')
ax2.set_xlabel('Conservation Status', fontsize=12)
ax2.set_ylabel('Species Category', fontsize=12)

# 3. Standardized residuals
residuals = (contingency - expected_df) / np.sqrt(expected_df)
sns.heatmap(residuals, annot=True, fmt='.2f', cmap='RdBu_r', center=0,
           cbar_kws={'label': 'Standardized Residual'}, linewidths=0.5, ax=ax3)
ax3.set_title('Standardized Residuals', fontsize=13, fontweight='bold')
ax3.set_xlabel('Conservation Status', fontsize=12)
ax3.set_ylabel('Species Category', fontsize=12)

# 4. Percentage composition by category
contingency_pct = contingency.div(contingency.sum(axis=1), axis=0) * 100
contingency_pct.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, ax=ax4, colormap='Set3', alpha=0.8)
ax4.set_title('Conservation Status Distribution by Category (%)', fontsize=13, fontweight='bold')
ax4.set_xlabel('Species Category', fontsize=12)
ax4.set_ylabel('Percentage', fontsize=12)
ax4.tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45)
ax4.legend(title='Conservation Status', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left', fontsize=9)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Statistical results and interpretation
print(f"\nSTATISTICAL TEST RESULTS:")
print("=" * 35)
print(f"Chi-squared statistic (): {chi2:.4f}")
print(f"p-value: {pval:.2e}")
print(f"Degrees of freedom: {dof}")
print(f"Cramr's V (effect size): {cramers_v:.4f}")

# Effect size interpretation
if cramers_v < 0.1:
    effect_interpretation = "Negligible"
elif cramers_v < 0.3:
    effect_interpretation = "Small"
elif cramers_v < 0.5:
    effect_interpretation = "Medium"
else:
    effect_interpretation = "Large"

print(f"Effect size interpretation: {effect_interpretation}")

# Statistical conclusion
alpha = 0.05
print(f"\nSTATISTICAL CONCLUSION:")
print("=" * 30)
print(f"Significance level (): {alpha}")
print(f"Decision criterion: p-value {'<' if pval < alpha else ''} ")

if pval < alpha:
    print(f"REJECT the null hypothesis")
    print(f"Conclusion: There IS a statistically significant relationship")
    print(f"   between species category and conservation status.")
    print(f"   The observed differences are unlikely due to chance alone.")
else:
    print(f"FAIL TO REJECT the null hypothesis")
    print(f"Conclusion: There is NO statistically significant relationship")
    print(f"   between species category and conservation status.")
    print(f"   Observed differences could be due to random variation.")

# Practical significance
print(f"\nPRACTICAL IMPLICATIONS:")
print("=" * 30)
if pval < alpha and cramers_v > 0.1:
    print(f"Both statistically AND practically significant")
    print(f"Conservation efforts should be category-specific")
    print(f"Different species groups require tailored protection strategies")
elif pval < alpha and cramers_v <= 0.1:
    print(f"Statistically significant but small effect size")
    print(f"Relationship exists but may not be practically important")
else:
    print(f"No evidence for category-specific conservation patterns")
    print(f"General conservation approaches may be sufficient")

# Detailed residual analysis
print(f"\nRESIDUAL ANALYSIS (|residual| > 2.0 indicates significant deviation):")
print("=" * 70)
significant_residuals = []
for i, category in enumerate(contingency.index):
    for j, status in enumerate(contingency.columns):
        residual = residuals.iloc[i, j]
        if abs(residual) > 2.0:
            direction = "higher" if residual > 0 else "lower"
            significant_residuals.append((category, status, residual, direction))
            print(f"   {category} - {status}: {residual:.2f} ({direction} than expected)")

if not significant_residuals:
    print("   No significant deviations from expected frequencies detected")

# Post-hoc analysis for significant results
if pval < alpha:
    print(f"\nPOST-HOC ANALYSIS:")
    print("=" * 25)
    
    # Find the most concerning category-status combinations
    concern_statuses = ['Endangered', 'Threatened', 'Species of Concern', 'In Recovery']
    for status in concern_statuses:
        if status in contingency.columns:
            status_data = contingency[status].sort_values(ascending=False)
            total_in_status = status_data.sum()
            if total_in_status > 0:
                top_category = status_data.index[0]
                top_count = status_data.iloc[0]
                percentage = (top_count / total_in_status) * 100
                print(f"   {status}: {top_category} dominates with {top_count} species ({percentage:.1f}%)")

# Data quality considerations
print(f"\nDATA QUALITY CONSIDERATIONS:")
print("=" * 35)
total_species_original = len(species_info_df)
species_analyzed = len(analysis_df)
coverage_percentage = (species_analyzed / total_species_original) * 100
print(f"   Analysis Coverage: {species_analyzed:,} of {total_species_original:,} species ({coverage_percentage:.1f}%)")
print(f"   Missing Conservation Data: {total_species_original - species_analyzed:,} species")

if coverage_percentage < 50:
    print(f"  WARNING: Low conservation status coverage may limit generalizability")
elif coverage_percentage < 80:
    print(f"  CAUTION: Moderate conservation status coverage")
else:
    print(f"  GOOD: High conservation status coverage supports robust conclusions")
